<HEADLINE>
<P>
DODGERS RUN WILD, STILL WIN; BASEBALL: DESPITE STRANGE PLAYS, THEY RALLY TO 
DEFEAT PHILLIES, 4-3. WORRELL GETS THE SAVE. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MARYANN HUDSON, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 They kept their manager squirming on the bench, and even made three outs at 
the plate in one inning, something Tom Lasorda said he had "not hardly" seen 
before.  
</P>
<P>
 But in a wild seventh inning, the Dodgers still managed to score the decisive 
runs in a 4-3 victory over the Philadelphia Phillies on Tuesday night at Dodger 
Stadium before 28,194. 
</P>
<P>
 "These guys are all doing their job and when they make mistakes, they make up 
for them with desire and effort," Lasorda said. "I like their attitude and the 
way they help each other and battle back." 
</P>
<P>
 Down 2-0, the Dodgers tied the score in the sixth when Eric Karros singled in 
Tim Wallach and scored on a single by Jeff Treadway. 
</P>
<P>
 Then came the seventh, an inning in which all three Dodger outs were made at 
the plate. The Dodgers scored twice to move ahead, 4-2, but the wildest moment 
came at the end, when the Phillies made a 9-2-3-5-2 play to abruptly stop a 
rally and send scorers into puzzlement. 
</P>
<P>
 "I wasn't too happy, " Lasorda said. "Poor Henry (Rodriguez), to see a guy 
slip, I thought he hurt himself." 
</P>
<P>
 With the bases loaded and one out, Jose Offerman scored on a single by 
Rodriguez. Eric Karros then grounded back to reliever Heathcliff Slocumb to 
force Mike Piazza at the plate. 
</P>
<P>
 Then, it got tricky. 
</P>
<P>
 Raul Mondesi hit a line drive to right field, which scored Tim Wallach. But 
Rodriguez, also trying to score, fell rounding third base. Right fielder Wes 
Chamberlain threw to catcher Darren Daulton, and Rodriguez, scrambling to his 
feet, went back to third. But Karros and Mondesi were running full bore, and 
when they saw Rodriguez stumble, they went into retreat. 
</P>
<P>
 "There was nothing I could do but stop," said Karros, who was two for four. "I 
saw (third base coach Joey) Amalfitano waving Henry in, so I just put my head 
down and kept running. But we were up 4-2, so it wasn't like we didn't score 
any runs." 
</P>
<P>
 Daulton threw to John Kruk to try to get Mondesi, or somebody, and Kruk threw 
to third baseman Dave Hollins, who realized by then that Rodriguez was headed 
for home, so Hollins made the throw to the plate for the third out. 
</P>
<P>
 "If we would have lost, it would have been tough," said Wallach, who scored 
two runs.  
</P>
<P>
 For the Dodgers, whose last seven losses have been by two runs or less, a 
two-run lead in the eighth inning doesn't provide a very secure feeling. 
</P>
<P>
 So when the Phillies came back to score a run in the eighth, Lasorda put the 
ball in Todd Worrell's hands. Worrell retired the side in order to earn his 
second save. Gary Wayne (1-2), who relieved starter Kevin Gross to start the 
seventh inning, earned the victory. 
</P>
<P>
 "The Phillies had opportunities to score and we did too, but when they had the 
bases loaded in the sixth inning and Kevin got out of it, that was the key," 
Wallach said.  
</P>
<P>
 Gross, who has made four starts and still doesn't have a decision, held the 
Phillies to two runs, but it could have been much worse. 
</P>
<P>
 In a wild sixth inning, Gross loaded the bases when he walked Darren Daulton, 
took off Milt Thompson's helmet with a pitch high and inside and saw Treadway 
boot Kevin Stocker's routine grounder. But Gross pitched out of that jam, 
coming back to strike out Ricky Jordan, who was pinch-hitting for Greene, and 
popping up Lenny Dykstra. 
</P>
<P>
 "It made it exciting," Gross said. "I threw too many pitches, but we battled 
and I kept it close and we won. I would love to have as many wins as I can, but 
we win as a team and that is the most important thing." 
</P>
<P>
 Against Philly starter Tommy Greene, the Dodgers stranded six baserunners in 
the first five innings and in four of those innings, they had runners in 
scoring position. Each team stranded 10 baserunners.  
</P>
<P>
 Greene made his first start since April 7 and held the Dodgers to three hits 
through five innings. Greene, who had been sidelined with shoulder tendinitis, 
gave up four walks, two in the third inning, but the Dodgers didn't take 
advantage.  
</P>
<P>
 "We knew we would get them eventually," Karros said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
