<HEADLINE>
<P>
STANLEY CUP PLAYOFFS; EASTWOOD'S GOAL LIFTS MAPLE LEAFS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Mike Eastwood, playing because of an injury to Doug Gilmour, made the most of 
an opportunity. 
</P>
<P>
 Eastwood scored the game's only goal with 13 seconds left in a third-period 
power play, giving the Toronto Maple Leafs a 1-0 victory over the Chicago 
Blackhawks at Toronto and a 3-2 lead in their Western Conference quarterfinal 
playoff series. 
</P>
<P>
 "It's a tremendous relief," Eastwood said of his first playoff goal, scored at 
10:07 of the third period. "I was just happy to be in the right place at the 
right time." 
</P>
<P>
 Toronto's opportunity came when Gary Suter was penalized for hooking at 8:20. 
Dave Andreychuk passed out of the corner to Eastwood, who put it over Ed 
Belfour's shoulder. 
</P>
<P>
 "Wendel (Clark) made a great play behind the net to get the puck over to Dave 
and I just got a piece of it." 
</P>
<P>
 Vancouver 2, Calgary 1 -- Geoff Courtnall's goal 7:15 into overtime at Calgary 
kept the Canucks alive in the playoffs, cutting their deficit to 3-2 in a 
Western Conference quarterfinal series. 
</P>
<P>
 Calgary could have closed out the series by winning on its home ice, but 
instead Vancouver won the right to play host to Game 6 on Thursday night at 
Vancouver. 
</P>
<P>
 The game turned on a defensive mistake. Calgary's Kevin Dahl was unable to 
control a bouncing puck near center ice and Courtnall took over. He broke in 
alone and scored on a 35-foot slap shot. 
</P>
<P>
 San Jose 6, Detroit 4 -- Sergei Makarov scored twice and Igor Larionov had 
three assists at San Jose to help the eighth-seeded Sharks take a 3-2 lead in 
the Western Conference quarterfinal series. 
</P>
<P>
 Makarov scored the Sharks' first goal on a power play 2:47 into the game. 
After another first-period goal by Todd Elik, Detroit rallied to tie the score 
on goals by Paul Coffey and Ray Sheppard. 
</P>
<P>
 Makarov scored his second goal with only 75 seconds to play in the second 
period, putting the Sharks ahead to stay. San Jose was outshot, 35-21, but 
Arturs Irbe stopped 31 shots. 
</P>
</TEXT>
