<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: ORANGE; THE SETTING WAS GROUNDS FOR MARRIAGE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MARTIN MILLER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Week after week, over coffee, Barbara Robinson and John Beringer debated war, 
politics and religion. They should have known love wasn't far behind. 
</P>
<P>
 Surrounded by friends and family, Beringer and Robinson were married Saturday 
in Cyrano's Coffee House in Orange, where they had met just over four months 
ago. 
</P>
<P>
 "It's not as impulsive as it sounds," said Robinson, 45, a Superior Court 
clerk from Orange. "I just can't think of anyone else in the world I'd rather 
be with than him." 
</P>
<P>
 The relationship began brewing at a weekly coffeehouse discussion group. The 
group of about 20, ranging in age from 12 to 90, tackled a broad range of 
topics -- everything from gays in the military to quantum mechanics. 
</P>
<P>
 Beringer 43, a professional mediator from Tustin, said he quickly became 
enchanted with Robinson's passion and honesty when addressing the group. 
</P>
<P>
 "I loved watching her open up," said Beringer, who helped found the group. 
"Her insights into things, the way her mind works, it's really beautiful. She's 
a remarkable lady." 
</P>
<P>
 It was, alas, almost a relationship that didn't happen. Robinson said had it 
not been for a friend who practically dragged her to the coffeehouse, she never 
would have gone. 
</P>
<P>
 Unexpectedly, Beringer and Robinson found the coffeehouse atmosphere a welcome 
relief from the bar scene, which they found superficial. With the aroma of 
coffee and compelling ideas in the air, Robinson and Beringer felt comfortable 
enough to be themselves. 
</P>
<P>
 "The dating scene can be so phony," Beringer said. "I had really given up on 
dating, and dating services didn't seem to work. But Cyrano's was really 
special. It's the place we met, and (it) allowed us to sustain our 
relationship." 
</P>
<P>
 Robinson agreed: "There's just so few places where you can sit and talk openly 
and honestly about how you feel." 
</P>
<P>
 When the time came to plan the wedding, there was no doubt where it was going 
to be: Cyrano's. 
</P>
<P>
 "We are terribly romantic, and that's where we met and fell in love with each 
other," Robinson said. "It's a very special place to us." 
</P>
<P>
 The couple plan to honeymoon in Laguna Beach. "We are just going to sit there 
and watch the sun set," Beringer said.MARTIN MILLER 
</P>
</TEXT>
